 1997, most words in the English language are spelled phonetically and many of them are pronounced differently than they were in 1897.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/interviews/a15810/teller-magician-interview-1012/|title=Chris Jones on How Teller Got His Magic Back|date=September 17, 2012|website=Esquire.com|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Eon (novel)|Eon]]''\n| Novel\n| 1985\n| 2005\n|In 2005, the United States and a still-extant Soviet Union are on the brink of nuclear war. \n|-\n| ''[[Escape from L.A.]]''\n| Film\n| 1996\n| 2000\u20132013\n| The film predicts a massive earthquake that floods the [[San Fernando Valley]] in 2000, rendering Los Angeles an island.<ref name=\"movie pilot\"/> The US capital is moved to [[Lynchburg, Virginia]] after an evangelist from there becomes US president for life.\n|-\n| ''[[Escape from Mars]]''\n| TV film\n| 1999\n| 2015\u20132016\n| The first manned mission to Mars is launched on June 4, 2015.\n|-\n| ''[[Escape from New York]]''\n| Film\n| 1981\n| 1997\n| Predicts a 400% rise in crime rate in 1988, prompting the remaking of [[Manhattan|Manhattan Island]] into a nationwide maximum security prison with no guards. In reality, [[Crime in the United States|crime rates in the US]] peaked in the film's release year of 1981, were about 20% lower in 1997 and have continued to drop ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/1981the-year-of-nyc-crime-that-inspired-a-most-violent-year/|title=1981, The Year Of NYC Crime That Inspired 'A Most Violent Year'|author=|date=January 2, 2015|website=uproxx.com|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MLCijEXbZGAC&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=1981+peak+crime|title=Criminal Victimization in the U.S. 1991: A National Crime Victimization Survey Report|first=DIANE Publishing|last=Company|date=April 1, 1993|publisher=DIANE Publishing|accessdate=December 9, 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780788106552}}</ref><!-- movie pilot, complex -->\n|-\n| \"[[Essence of Life (The Outer Limits)|Essence of Life]]\" (from ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1999\n| 2014\n| In 2014, Earth is struggling to rebuild after a devastating plague.\n|-\n| \"[[Epitaph Two: Return]]\" (from '' [[Dollhouse (TV series)|Dollhouse]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2010\n| 2020\n| Post-apocalypse in which most of humanity have had their minds wiped.\n|-\n| ''[[El Eternauta]]''\n| Comic\n| 1957\u20131959\n| 1963\n| Depicts an [[alien invasion]] of [[Argentina]].\n|-\n| ''[[Eternity Weeps]]'' (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| Novel\n| 1997\n| 2003\n| In 2003, there is a colony on the Moon, there are border skirmishes between [[Turkey]] and [[Iran]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]] is the US president.\n|-\n| ''[[Ever 17: The Out of Infinity]]''\n| Video game\n| 2002\n| 2017\n|A cure for aging has been developed and a deadly virus outbreak occurs. \n|-\n| ''[[Fahrenheit (2005 video game)|Fahrenheit]]''\n| Video game\n| 2005\n| 2009\n|Also known as ''Indigo Prophecy'' in North America; refers to the [[2012 phenomenon]] and [[indigo children]]. \n|-\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Novel\n| 1953\n| data-sort-value=\"1960\"| After 1960\n| Early editions listed some time after 1960. Later editions showed after 1990 or 2022, where they started and won two atomic wars.<!-- 50th anniversary edition, page 73, see [[Fahrenheit 451#cite note-15|footnote]] --> Predicted regular use of [[earbud headphones]],<ref name=\"bustle\"/> [[interactive television]], [[video wall]] screens, robotic [[bank teller]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/dreams-of-ray-bradbury-ten-predictions-that-came-true/2012/06/06/gJQAqbs9IV_story.html|title=Dreams of Ray Bradbury: Predictions that came true|first=Hayley|last=Tsukayama|date=June 6, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=January 19, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> the demise of [[newspaper]]s and the prevalent use of [[factoid]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/06/ray-bradbury-dead-how-accurate-predictions-fahrenheit-451_n_1574126.html|title=Five Predictions Sci-Fi Author Ray Bradbury Got Right|author=|date=June 6, 2012|website=huffingtonpost.co.uk|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> Also had the [[Mechanical Hound]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://clclt.com/charlotte/dystopian-classic-fahrenheit-451-still-strikes-sparks/Content?oid=6923191|title=Dystopian Classic 'Fahrenheit 451' Still Strikes Sparks|first=Pat|last=Moran|date=|website=Creative Loafing Charlotte|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> and technology for complete [[blood transfusions]].\n|-\n| \"Fast Forward\" (from ''[[The Flash (1990 TV series)|The Flash]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1991\n| 2001\n| The [[Flash (Barry Allen)]] is accidentally sent ten years forward in time to March 3, 2001.\n|-\n| \"[[Fear Her]]\" (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2006\n| 2012\n|This episode takes place during the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Fire Next Time (miniseries)|The Fire Next Time]]''\n| TV miniseries\n| 1993\n| 2017\n| In 2017, the [[greenhouse effect]] and [[global warming]] have resulted in widespread droughts, floods, hurricanes and the outbreak of fires which have wreaked devastation over Earth.\n|-\n|''[[Firebird 2015 AD]]''\n| Film\n| 1981\n| 2015\n|By 2015, public ownership of motor vehicles and gasoline is punishable by summary execution. \n|-\n|''[[First Spaceship on Venus]]''\n| Film\n| 1960\n| 1985\n| The [[Gobi Desert]] is irrigated in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedailymirror/2010/06/from-the-vaults-first-spaceship-on-venus-1960.html|title=From the Vaults: 'First Spaceship on Venus' (1960)|author=|date=June 7, 2010|website=Latimes.com|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Fist of the North Star]]''\n| Manga\n| 1983\u20131988\n|data-sort-value=\"1990\"| 199X\n|''[[Mad Max]]''-inspired post-nuclear wasteland in which superpowered martial artists fight each other for dominance. The world is described as having been devastated by a series of nuclear wars in the 1990s. \n|-\n| ''[[Flashforward (novel)|Flashforward]]''\n| Novel\n| 1999\n| 2009\n| The novel correctly predicted that the [[Large Hadron Collider]] would be operational by 2009 and that a pope named [[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] would be in office in that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scifi.stackexchange.com/questions/121293/what-predictions-about-2009-and-beyond-did-the-novel-flashforward-get-right-and|title=What predictions about 2009 and beyond did the novel Flashforward get right and wrong?|author=|date=|website=scifi.stackexchange.com|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amc.com/talk/2009/09/flashforward-au|title=FlashForward Author Robert J. Sawyer on How George Lucas Pre-Empted His SciFi Series|author=AMC Staff|date=2009 |website=Amc.com|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sfwriter.com/2007/10/forbescom-interviews-robert-j-sawyer.html|title=Forbes.com interviews Robert J. Sawyer | date=October 16, 2007 | first=Robert J. | last=Sawyer | website=SFWriter (Robert J. Sawyer official website) | authorlink=Robert J. Sawyer | accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Flow My Tears, the Policeman Said]]''\n| Novel\n| 1974\n| 1988\n|In 1988, the United States is a fascist police state following a Second Civil War. The black population is nearly extinct and personal aircraft are common. \n|-\n| ''[[The Flying Torpedo]]''\n| Film\n| 1916\n| 1921\n| In 1921, foreign spies steal a radio-controlled flying bomb and plan to use it to attack the United States as a prelude to invasion.\n|-\n|''[[Sheldon Allman|Folk Songs for the 21st Century]]''\n|Album\n|1960\n|2001\u20132020\n|Nuclear war occurs in the 21st century.\n|-\n| ''[[For Us, The Living: A Comedy of Customs]]''\n| Novel\n| 1939\n| 1940\u20131970\n| Published in 2003. The novel correctly predicted that [[Adolf Hitler]] would commit suicide after his plans of conquest were defeated.\n|-\n| ''[[The Forge of God]]''\n| Novel\n| 1987\n| 1996\n|An alien race destroys the Earth, but a small fragment of humanity are preserved by another alien race. \n|-\n| ''[[Fortress (1992 film)|Fortress]]''\n| Film\n| 1992\n| 2017\n| The US limits families to only one child.<ref name=\"ds7\"/><ref name=\"movie pilot\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Fourth Protocol]]''\n| Novel\n| 1984\n| 1986\u20131987\n|Correctly predicted that [[Margaret Thatcher]] would call a General Election in the United Kingdom in June 1987.\n|-\n| \"[[Franchise (short story)|Franchise]]\"\n| Short story\n| 1955\n| 2008\n|In [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]], the US president is elected via means of a computer, which calculates and determines the most suitable candidate for the post.\n|-\n| ''[[Frankenstein 1970]]''\n| Film\n| 1958\n| 1970\n| The monster is created using an [[atomic reactor]]. \n|-\n| ''[[Freejack]]''\n| Film\n| 1992\n| 2009\n| The main characters travel forward in time to November 2009. Time travel is commonplace and criminals travel back in time to kidnap victims for organ harvesting.<ref name=\"complex\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Futurama (New York World's Fair)|Futurama]]''\n| Exhibit\n| 1939\n| 1959\n|Predicted an [[automated highway system]].\n|-\n|''[[Future Fear]]''\n| Film\n| 1997\n| 2018\n| Predicted computers with AI [[Voice user interface|voice assistants]], a voice-activated record player, bars with automatic electronic bouncer systems, and hand-held [[Laser weapon|laser-guns]]. Also predicted a conspiracy between US politicians and members of the military to commit mass genocide using an alien virus in order to establish a [[Fourth Reich]].\n|-\n| ''[[Xin Zhongguo weilai ji|Future of a New China]]''\n| Novel\n| 1902\n| 1903\u20131962\n| In 1962, China is a utopia, a world power, wealthy, Confucian and a constitutional monarchy.\n|-\n| \"[[Future-Drama]]\"<br>(''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode)\n| TV series episode\n| 2005\n| 2013\n|By 2013, underwater homes and 3D holographic recording are possible. \n|-\n| ''[[Future Boy Conan]]''\n| Anime series\n| 1978\n| 2008\n| In July 2008, the Earth's continents are violently torn apart by a nuclear war, sinking most of them under the sea.\n|-\n| ''[[Future Schlock]]''\n| Film\n| 1984\n| 1990\n| As a result of the class wars in 1990, the [[middle class]] has mandated that people be middling or dull. Non-conformists are imprisoned in the inner city ghetto.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/future-schlock-1984/604/ |title=Future Schlock (1984) - The Screen Guide |website=Screen Australia |access-date=January 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710041014/https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/future-schlock-1984/604/ |archive-date=July 10, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/future-schlock|title=Future Schlock \u2013 Review \u2013 Photos \u2013 Ozmovies|website=Ozmovies.com.au|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Futureworld]]''\n| Film\n| 1976\n| 1985\n| Sequel to ''[[Westworld (film)|Westworld]]'' and also set mainly in a theme park filled with androids.<ref name=\"diffuser\">{{cite web|url=http://diffuser.fm/futureworld-movie/|title='Futureworld' \u2013 A Look Back at the First Movie With 3D CGI|first=Michael|last=Gallucci|date=February 7, 2014|work=[[Diffuser.fm]]|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Galactix]]''\n| Video game\n| 1991\n| 2019\n| In 2019, amid devastating [[global climate change]] triggered by the final depletion of the [[Amazon rain forest|Amazon rainforest]], Earth is threatened with invasion and enslavement by a powerful force of alien cyborgs, known in-game as the \"Xidus\".\n|-\n| ''[[Genesis II (film)|Genesis II]]''\n| [[TV pilot]]\n| 1973\n| 1979\n| The movie opens in 1979, with the main character entering suspended animation. The bulk of the film (and the subsequent series, 