 4, 2015.\n|-\n| ''[[Escape from New York]]''\n| Film\n| 1981\n| 1997\n| Predicts a 400% rise in crime rate in 1988, prompting the remaking of [[Manhattan|Manhattan Island]] into a nationwide maximum security prison with no guards. In reality, [[Crime in the United States|crime rates in the US]] peaked in the film's release year of 1981, were about 20% lower in 1997 and have continued to drop ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uproxx.com/movies/1981the-year-of-nyc-crime-that-inspired-a-most-violent-year/|title=1981, The Year Of NYC Crime That Inspired 'A Most Violent Year'|author=|date=January 2, 2015|website=uproxx.com|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=MLCijEXbZGAC&pg=PA3&lpg=PA3&dq=1981+peak+crime|title=Criminal Victimization in the U.S. 1991: A National Crime Victimization Survey Report|first=DIANE Publishing|last=Company|date=April 1, 1993|publisher=DIANE Publishing|accessdate=December 9, 2017|via=Google Books|isbn=9780788106552}}</ref><!-- movie pilot, complex -->\n|-\n| \"[[Essence of Life (The Outer Limits)|Essence of Life]]\" (from ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1999\n| 2014\n| In 2014, Earth is struggling to rebuild after a devastating plague.\n|-\n| \"[[Epitaph Two: Return]]\" (from '' [[Dollhouse (TV series)|Dollhouse]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2010\n| 2020\n| Post-apocalypse in which most of humanity have had their minds wiped.\n|-\n| ''[[El Eternauta]]''\n| Comic\n| 1957\u20131959\n| 1963\n| Depicts an [[alien invasion]] of [[Argentina]].\n|-\n| ''[[Eternity Weeps]]'' (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| Novel\n| 1997\n| 2003\n| In 2003, there is a colony on the Moon, there are border skirmishes between [[Turkey]] and [[Iran]] and [[Bruce Springsteen]] is the US president.\n|-\n| ''[[Ever 17: The Out of Infinity]]''\n| Video game\n| 2002\n| 2017\n|A cure for aging has been developed and a deadly virus outbreak occurs. \n|-\n| ''[[Fahrenheit (2005 video game)|Fahrenheit]]''\n| Video game\n| 2005\n| 2009\n|Also known as ''Indigo Prophecy'' in North America; refers to the [[2012 phenomenon]] and [[indigo children]]. \n|-\n| ''[[Fahrenheit 451]]''\n| Novel\n| 1953\n| data-sort-value=\"1960\"| After 1960\n| Early editions listed some time after 1960. Later editions showed after 1990 or 2022, where they started and won two atomic wars.<!-- 50th anniversary edition, page 73, see [[Fahrenheit 451#cite note-15|footnote]] --> Predicted regular use of [[earbud headphones]],<ref name=\"bustle\"/> [[interactive television]], [[video wall]] screens, robotic [[bank teller]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/dreams-of-ray-bradbury-ten-predictions-that-came-true/2012/06/06/gJQAqbs9IV_story.html|title=Dreams of Ray Bradbury: Predictions that came true|first=Hayley|last=Tsukayama|date=June 6, 2012|publisher=|accessdate=January 19, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref> the demise of [[newspaper]]s and the prevalent use of [[factoid]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2012/06/06/ray-bradbury-dead-how-accurate-predictions-fahrenheit-451_n_1574126.html|title=Five Predictions Sci-Fi Author Ray Bradbury Got Right|author=|date=June 6, 2012|website=huffingtonpost.co.uk|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> Also had the [[Mechanical Hound]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://clclt.com/charlotte/dystopian-classic-fahrenheit-451-still-strikes-sparks/Content?oid=6923191|title=Dystopian Classic 'Fahrenheit 451' Still Strikes Sparks|first=Pat|last=Moran|date=|website=Creative Loafing Charlotte|accessdate=January 19, 2018}}</ref> and technology for complete [[blood transfusions]].\n|-\n| \"Fast Forward\" (from ''[[The Flash (1990 TV series)|The Flash]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1991\n| 2001\n| The [[Flash (Barry Allen)]] is accidentally sent ten years forward in time to March 3, 2001.\n|-\n| \"[[Fear Her]]\" (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2006\n| 2012\n|This episode takes place during the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Fire Next Time (miniseries)|The Fire Next Time]]''\n| TV miniseries\n| 1993\n| 2017\n| In 2017, the [[greenhouse effect]] and [[global warming]] have resulted in widespread droughts, floods, hurricanes and the outbreak of fires which have wreaked devastation over Earth.\n|-\n|''[[Firebird 2015 AD]]''\n| Film\n| 1981\n| 2015\n|By 2015, public ownership of motor vehicles and gasoline is punishable by summary execution. \n|-\n|''[[First Spaceship on Venus]]''\n| Film\n| 1960\n| 1985\n| The [[Gobi Desert]] is irrigated in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/thedailymirror/2010/06/from-the-vaults-first-spaceship-on-venus-1960.html|title=From the Vaults: 'First Spaceship on Venus' (1960)|author=|date=June 7, 2010|website=Latimes.com|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Fist of the North Star]]''\n| Manga\n| 1983\u20131988\n|data-sort-value=\"1990\"| 199X\n|''[[Mad Max]]''-inspired post-nuclear wasteland in which superpowered martial artists fight each other for dominance. The world is described as having been devastated by a series of nuclear wars in the 1990s. \n|-\n| ''[[Flashforward (novel)|Flashforward]]''\n| Novel\n| 1999\n| 2009\n| The novel correctly predicted that the [[Large Hadron Collider]] would be operational by 2009 and that a pope named [[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] would be in office in that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scifi.stackexchange.com/questions/121293/what-predictions-about-2009-and-beyond-did-the-novel-flashforward-get-right-and|title=What predictions about 2009 and beyond did the novel Flashforward get right and wrong?|author=|date=|website=scifi.stackexchange.com|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amc.com/talk/2009/09/flashforward-au|title=FlashForward Author Robert J. Sawyer on How George Lucas Pre-Empted His SciFi Series|author=AMC Staff|date=2009 |website=Amc.com|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sfwriter.com/2007/10/forbescom-interviews-robert-j-sawyer.html|title=Forbes.com interviews Robert J. Sawyer | date=October 16, 2007 | first=Robert J. | last=Sawyer | website=SFWriter (Robert J. Sawyer official website) | authorlink=Robert J. Sawyer | accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Flow My Tears, the Policeman Said]]''\n| Novel\n| 1974\n| 1988\n|In 1988, the United States is a fascist police state following a Second Civil War. The black population is nearly extinct and personal aircraft are common. \n|-\n| ''[[The Flying Torpedo]]''\n| Film\n| 1916\n| 1921\n| In 1921, foreign spies steal a radio-controlled flying bomb and plan to use it to attack the United States as a prelude to invasion.\n|-\n|''[[Sheldon Allman|Folk Songs for the 21st Century]]''\n|Album\n|1960\n|2001\u20132020\n|Nuclear war occurs in the 21st century.\n|-\n| ''[[For Us, The Living: A Comedy of Customs]]''\n| Novel\n| 1939\n| 1940\u20131970\n| Published in 2003. The novel correctly predicted that [[Adolf Hitler]] would commit suicide after his plans of conquest were defeated.\n|-\n| ''[[The Forge of God]]''\n| Novel\n| 1987\n| 1996\n|An alien race destroys the Earth, but a small fragment of humanity are preserved by another alien race. \n|-\n| ''[[Fortress (1992 film)|Fortress]]''\n| Film\n| 1992\n| 2017\n| The US limits families to only one child.<ref name=\"ds7\"/><ref name=\"movie pilot\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Fourth Protocol]]''\n| Novel\n| 1984\n| 1986\u20131987\n|Correctly predicted that [[Margaret Thatcher]] would call a General Election in the United Kingdom in June 1987.\n|-\n| \"[[Franchise (short story)|Franchise]]\"\n| Short story\n| 1955\n| 2008\n|In [[2008 United States presidential election|2008]], the US president is elected via means of a computer, which calculates and determines the most suitable candidate for the post.\n|-\n| ''[[Frankenstein 1970]]''\n| Film\n| 1958\n| 1970\n| The monster is created using an [[atomic reactor]]. \n|-\n| ''[[Freejack]]''\n| Film\n| 1992\n| 2009\n| The main characters travel forward in time to November 2009. Time travel is commonplace and criminals travel back in time to kidnap victims for organ harvesting.<ref name=\"complex\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Futurama (New York World's Fair)|Futurama]]''\n| Exhibit\n| 1939\n| 1959\n|Predicted an [[automated highway system]].\n|-\n|''[[Future Fear]]''\n| Film\n| 1997\n| 2018\n| Predicted computers with AI [[Voice user interface|voice assistants]], a voice-activated record player, bars with automatic electronic bouncer systems, and hand-held [[Laser weapon|laser-guns]]. Also predicted a conspiracy between US politicians and members of the military to commit mass genocide using an alien virus in order to establish a [[Fourth Reich]].\n|-\n| ''[[Xin Zhongguo weilai ji|Future of a New China]]''\n| Novel\n| 1902\n| 1903\u20131962\n| In 1962, China is a utopia, a world power, wealthy, Confucian and a constitutional monarchy.\n|-\n| \"[[Future-Drama]]\"<br>(''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode)\n| TV series episode\n| 2005\n| 2013\n|By 2013, underwater homes and 3D holographic recording are possible. \n|-\n| ''[[Future Boy Conan]]''\n| Anime series\n| 1978\n| 2008\n| In July 2008, the Earth's continents are violently torn apart by a nuclear war, sinking most of them under the sea.\n|-\n| ''[[Future Schlock]]''\n| Film\n| 1984\n| 1990\n| As a result of the class wars in 1990, the [[middle class]] has mandated that people be middling or dull. Non-conformists are imprisoned in the inner city ghetto.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/future-schlock-1984/604/ |title=Future Schlock (1984) - The Screen Guide |website=Screen Australia |access-date=January 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180710041014/https://www.screenaustralia.gov.au/the-screen-guide/t/future-schlock-1984/604/ |archive-date=July 10, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ozmovies.com.au/movie/future-schlock|title=Future Schlock \u2013 Review \u2013 Photos \u2013 Ozmovies|website=Ozmovies.com.au|accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Futureworld]]''\n| Film\n| 1976\n| 1985\n| Sequel to ''[[Westworld (film)|Westworld]]'' and also set mainly in a theme park filled with androids.<ref name=\"diffuser\">{{cite web|url=http://diffuser.fm/futureworld-movie/|title='Futureworld' \u2013 A Look Back at the First Movie With 3D CGI|first=Michael|last=Gallucci|date=February 7, 2014|work=[[Diffuser.fm]]|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Galactix]]''\n| Video game\n| 1991\n| 2019\n| In 2019, amid devastating [[global climate change]] triggered by the final depletion of the [[Amazon rain forest|Amazon rainforest]], Earth is threatened with invasion and enslavement by a powerful force of alien cyborgs, known in-game as the \"Xidus\".\n|-\n| ''[[Genesis II (film)|Genesis II]]''\n| [[TV pilot]]\n| 1973\n| 1979\n| The movie opens in 1979, with the main character entering suspended animation. The bulk of the film (and the subsequent series, if it had been picked up) takes place in 2133.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://space1970.blogspot.com/2011/03/genesis-ii-1973.html|title=space1970: GENESIS II (1973)|first=Christopher|last=Mills|date=March 22, 2011|work=space1970.blogspot.com|accessdate=April 21, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| \"[[Gettysburg (The Outer Limits)|Gettysburg]]\" (from ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2000\n| 2013\n| This episode correctly predicted that the first African-American President of the United States would be in office by 2013.\n|-\n| ''[[Give Me Liberty]]''\n| Comic\n| 1990\n| 1995\u20132012\n|[[Martha Washington (comics)|Martha Washington]] is born on March 11, 1995.\n|-\n| ''[[Godzilla: Final Wars]]''\n| Film\n| 2004\n| 2020\n| In later years (around 2020), environmental disasters cause the appearance of giant monsters and superhumans, dubbed \"mutants\", who are then recruited into the Earth Defense Force (EDF) to battle the monsters.\n|-\n| ''[[The Golden Book of Springfield]]''\n| Novel\n| 1920\n| 2018\n| In 2018, the residents of [[Springfield, Illinois]] are working to transform the city into a utopian paradise.\n|-\n| ''[[Golf in the Year 2000]]''\n| Novel\n| 1892\n| 2000\n| A man falls asleep in 1892 and wakes up in the year 2000; trains are supersonic and golf and politics are the only activities not yet dominated by masculinized women.\n|-\n| ''[[Gorath]]''\n| Film\n| 1962\n| 1976\u20131982\n| In 1979, a manned spacecraft reaches Saturn. In 1980, scientists invent nuclear jet engines to attempt to move Earth away from a runaway planet on a collision course with it.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=G4GDBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA166|title=The Sci-Fi Movie Guide: The Universe of Film from Alien to Zardoz|first=Chris|last=Barsanti|date=September 22, 2014|publisher=Visible Ink Press|accessdate=January 5, 2018|via=Google Books|isbn=9781578595334}}</ref><!-- several other sci-fi film books also confirm 1979 -->\n|-\n| ''[[The Great Air Robbery]]''\n| Film\n| 1919\n| 1925\n|Depicts [[air pirates]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Great War in England in 1897]]''\n| Novel\n| 1894\n| 1897\n| In 1897, France and Russia invade the UK and make several early advances, but the tide is turned when Germany comes to the UK's aid.\n|-\n| ''[[The Guardians (TV series)|The Guardians]]''\n| TV series\n| 1971\n| 1980s\n| Following economic chaos in the 1980s, democratic government in the United Kingdom has been overthrown in a bloodless coup, the [[House of Windsor|Royal Family]] have fled into self-imposed exile and the UK is ruled autocratically by the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] Sir Timothy Hobson. Hobson is initially a pawn of 'the General': a military officer by the name of Roger, who later becomes [[Minister of Defence (United Kingdom)|Minister of Defence]].\n|-\n|''[[The Guns of the South]]''\n| Novel\n| 1992\n| 2014\n| The plot involves a gang of [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging|South African white supremacists]] who travel back in time to 1864 from 2014 to assist the rebelling [[Confederate States Army|Confederates]] in their war against the US.\n|-\n| ''[[Half-Life (video game)|Half-Life]]''\n| Video game\n| 1998\n| 2000s\n|A \"resonance cascade\" at a top secret laboratory opens a gateway to another universe. \n|-\n|''[[Hardware (film)|Hardware]]''\n|Film\n|1990\n|2000\n|Set on a post-apocalyptic Earth devastated by nuclear war. A scavenger discovers the head of a [[cyborg]] in the desert, and it later reanimates and goes on a murderous rampage.\n|-\n| ''[[Heatseeker (film)|Heatseeker]]''\n| Film\n| 1995\n| 2019\n|Cybernetic implants augment the abilities of martial artists.<ref name=\"express 2019\"/> \n|-\n| ''[[Harley Davidson and the Marlboro Man]]''\n| Film\n| 1991\n| 1996\n|A new [[designer drug]], crystal dream, is in common use.\n|-\n| \"Hello Tomorrow\" (from ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'')\n| Radio drama\n| 1950\n| 1991\n| In 1991, the Third Atomic War ended. The war left the surface of the Earth uninhabitable due to the high concentration of [[gamma ray]]s in the atmosphere. The survivors moved underground and eventually established a civilization. \n|-\n| ''[[High Treason (1929 British film)|High Treason]]''\n| Film\n| 1929\n| 1940/50\n|Concerns the threat of a [[Second World War]] between the \"United States of Europe\" and the \"Empire of the Atlantic States\".\n|-\n| ''[[Hong Kong 97 (film)|Hong Kong 97]]''\n| Film\n| 1994\n| 1997\n| Depicts the 1997 [[transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong]].\n|-\n| ''[[Hong Kong 97 (video game)|Hong Kong 97]]''\n| Video game\n| 1995\n| 1997\n| Set during the 1997 [[transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong]] by the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5936454/racism-violence--madness-make-this-awful-hong-kong-game-one-to-remember|title=Racism, Violence & Madness Make This Awful Hong Kong Game One to Remember|first=Luke|last=Plunkett|date=|website=Kotaku.com|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref> The game correctly predicted that [[Deng Xiaoping]] would die in 1997.\n|-\n| ''[[House of the Dead III]]''\n| Video game\n| 2002\n| 2019\n| Set 20 years after the events of the [[The House of the Dead (video game)|first game]], during a [[zombie apocalypse]]. \n|-\n| \"[[The Hungry Earth]]\"/\"[[Cold Blood (Doctor Who)|Cold Blood]]\" (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2010\n| 2020\"-ish\"\n| A group of [[Silurian (Doctor Who)|Silurians]] emerge in a [[Wales|Welsh]] village.\n|-\n|''[[Hunter Hunted (video game)|Hunter Hunted]]''\n| Video game\n| 1996\n| 2015\n|The world has been invaded, the human race exterminated and the survivors enslaved and forced to fight other captive aliens.\n|-\n| \"[[Hyperpilosity]]\"\n| Short story\n| 1938\n| 1971\n| In the Great Change of 1971, a virus infects humanity that causes everyone to grow fur all over their bodies.\n|-\n| ''[[I Am Legend (novel)|I Am Legend]]''\n| Novel\n| 1954\n| data-sort-value=\"1976\" | 1976\u20131979\n|A deadly virus outbreak in 1975 transforms all but one of the human race into [[vampires]]. \n|-\n| ''[[I Am Legend (film)|I Am Legend]]''\n| Film\n| 2007\n| 2009\u20132012\n| The film predicted an outbreak of a re-engineered measles virus in 2009 that kills 94% of the populace and mutates 5% into zombie-like \"Darkseekers\". Also predicted a ''[[Batman vs. Superman: Dawn of Justice|Batman vs. Superman]]'' film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/86080/15-movies-predicted-future|title=15 Movies That Predicted the Future|author=|date=September 15, 2016|work=mentalfloss.com|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"complex\"/> to be released in the film's future 2010.\n|-\n| \"[[I, James Blunt]]\"\n| Short story\n| 1942\n| 1944\u20131945\n| The United Kingdom is occupied by Nazi Germany in 1944 and 1945. [[St Paul's Cathedral]] is razed to make room for a [[British Nazi Party|Nazi Party]] headquarters and [[guerrilla warfare]] and any potential dissidence is suppressed through heavy policing.\n|-\n| ''[[I, Robot]]''\n| Film\n| 2004\n| 2020\n| The USR robotics company is founded in 2020.\n|-\n| ''[[Iceberg (Banks novel)|Iceberg]]'' (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| Novel\n| 1993\n| 1994\u20132006\n| The [[Planets beyond Neptune|tenth planet]] Cassius is discovered in 1994. [[Earth]]'s magnetic field reverses its polarity in 2006.\n|-\n| \"[[The Illusion of Truth]]\" (from ''[[Babylon 5]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1997\n| 2018\n| In 2018, the first permanent [[Colonization of the Moon|lunar colony]] was established in the [[Sea of Tranquility]].\n|-\n|''[[In 1999]]''\n|Play\n|1912\n|1999\n|Predicts a future in which [[Gender role|traditional gender roles]] are reversed, with women going to work and men staying at home.\n|-\n| ''[[Infinite Jest]]''\n| Novel\n| 1996\n| data-sort-value=\"2002\u20132010\"| c. 2002\u20132010\n| Starting sometime after 2001, each year is given a different sponsor name in a timeline called [[Infinite Jest#Subsidized Time|Subsidized Time]], of which one of the years involves the year 2007. The story discusses about this going into the ninth year of this format.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2010/07/archive-review-david-foster-wallaces-infinite-jest.html|title=Archive review: David Foster Wallace's 'Infinite Jest'|author=|date=July 31, 2010|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smallbytes.net/~bobkat/jest8.html|title=Modifying the Future : Review by David McLean|website=Smallbytes.net|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"burn readers guide\">{{citation|title = David Foster Wallace's Infinite Jest: A reader's guide|first = Stephen|last =  Burn|publisher = A&C Black|year = 2003|isbn = 082641477X|access-date = June 7, 2016|url = https://books.google.com/?id=xJ6U1VK3SRcC}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[In the Days of the Comet]]''\n| Novel\n| 1906\n| data-sort-value=\"1906\"|After 1906\n| A comet lands in 1906, spreading a green fog. Starting in ''Book II'', the narrator wakes up to find a more peaceful and rational 20th century society.\n|-\n| ''[[Insatiability]]''\n| Novel\n| 1930\n| 2000\n| In 2000, Poland is overrun by the army of the final [[Mongol invasions and conquests|Mongol conquest]]. The nation becomes enslaved to the Chinese leader Murti Bing. \n|-\n| ''[[In the Wet]]''\n| Novel\n| 1953\n| 1983\n| Set partially in 1983 where a mixed-race Australian pilot assists a Royal Family who are unloved in a Socialist UK.\n|-\n| ''[[Invasion! (2000 AD)|Invasion!]]''\n| Comic\n| 1977\u20131978\n| 1990\u20131999\n|A fascist Russia invades the UK. The sequel series ''Savage'', published from 2004 to the present, treats the events as alternate history.\n|-\n| ''[[The Invasion of 1910]]''\n| Novel\n| 1906\n| 1910\n| In 1910, Germany launches an invasion of the UK. The German forces eventually reach London and occupy half the city. Although London is later liberated, the war is a stalemate as Germany has occupied Belgium and the Netherlands.\n|-\n| ''[[Invasion of the Sea]]''\n| Novel\n| 1905\n| 1930s\n| In the 1930s, European engineers and their military escort seek to revive an actual 19th century proposal to flood the [[Sahara]] desert with waters from the Mediterranean Sea to create an inland \"[[Sahara Sea]]\" for both commercial and military purposes.\n|-\n| ''[[The Iron Heel]]''\n| Novel\n| 1908\n| 1910\u20131932\n| By 1910, the [[Socialist Party of America]] has become a major national party. An [[Oligarchy]] arises in the US from 1912 to 1932. Japan conquers East Asia and creates its own empire, India gains independence and Europe becomes socialist. Canada, Mexico, and Cuba form their own Oligarchies and are aligned with the United States.\n|-\n|''[[Iron Man 2020]]'' \n| Comic\n| 1984\n| 2020\n| The world is dominated by [[megacorporation]]s; [[virtual reality]] is the dominant form of entertainment. \n|-\n|''[[Iron Sky]]'' \n| Film\n| 2012\n| 2018\n| Takes place during the administration of a [[Sarah Palin]]-like US president; Nazis have been hiding out on the Moon.<ref name=\"mtv bad 80s\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Island (2005 film)|The Island]]''\n| Film\n| 2005\n| 2019\n| Human clones are kept alive and on standby for [[organ harvesting]].<ref name=\"express 2019\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[I Spit on Your Rave]]''\n| Short film\n| 2009\n| 2018\n| A virus unleashed during the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] initiates a [[zombie apocalypse]].\n|-\n| ''[[It Can't Happen Here]]''\n| Novel\n| 1935\n| 1936\n|Depicts [[Franklin Roosevelt]]'s loss of the [[1936 United States presidential election]] to a fascist populist.\n|-\n| ''[[It! The Terror from Beyond Space]]''\n| Film\n| 1958\n| 1973\n|The first manned mission to Mars returns to Earth in this year.\n|-\n| ''[[Jason X]]''\n| Film\n| 2001\n| 2008\u20132010\n| Jason Voorhees was captured by the US government in 2008 for experimentation and causes trouble in 2010 where he is cryogenically frozen. The rest of the movie takes place in outer space in 2455.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/jason-x-is-everything-that-makes-the-friday-the-13th-mo-1776319127 |title=Jason X Is Everything That Makes the Friday the 13th Movies Great... Just in Space |website=io9 |first=Germain |last=Lussier |date=May 13, 2016 |df=mdy}}</ref><!--  Ice hockey was outlawed in 2024. -->\n|-\n| ''[[The Jagged Orbit]]''\n| Novel\n| 1969\n| 2014\n|Racial tension in the United States has reached such a point that racial enclaves now exist throughout the country and paranoia and unrest are stoked by arms dealers. \n|-\n| ''[[The Janus Conjunction]]'' (from ''[[Doctor Who]]'')\n| Novel\n| 1998\n| 2011\n| [[San Francisco]] fell into the sea in 2011.\n|-\n| ''[[Jeremiah (TV series)|Jeremiah]]''\n| TV series\n| 2002\u20132004\n| 2006\n| In 2006, a plague wiped out almost everyone over the age of thirteen.\n|-\n|''[[Joe 90]]''\n|TV series\n|1968-1981\n|2012-2013\n|From the producers of ''[[Thunderbirds (TV series)|Thunderbirds]]''. Follows a young secret agent who can \"download\" skills into his brain.\n|-\n| \"[[The Joining (The Outer Limits)|The Joining]]\" (from ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1998\n| 2011\u20132012\n| Humanity has colonized [[Venus]] by 2011.\n|-\n| ''[[A Journey in Other Worlds]]''\n| Novel\n| 1894\n| 2000\n| By 2000, the United States is a superpower spanning multiple continents. By this time, solar power, air travel and space travel are commonplace. The Arctic Ocean is being dammed and Earth's [[axial tilt]] is being adjusted.\n|-\n| ''[[Journey into Space]]''\n| Radio series\n| 1953\u20131958\n| 1965\u20131972\n| The rocket Luna lands on the Moon on October 22, 1965 and the first moonwalk is broadcast to Earth over the radio. In April 1971, a mission to [[Mars]] is launched from the Moon.\n|-\n| ''[[Just Imagine]]''\n| Film\n| 1930\n| 1980\n| In 1980, personal airplanes are common in New York City, people have numbers instead of names, the US government will only permit people to marry if they are compatible and babies are readily procurable from vending machines. A manned mission to [[Mars]] is also depicted.\n|-\n| ''[[Kamikaze 1989]]''\n| Film\n| 1982\n| 1989\n|[[West Germany]] is now a totalitarian regime.<ref>{{cite web|title=KAMIKAZE 1989: A Fitting Farewell To Fassbinder|url=https://www.filminquiry.com/kamikaze-1989-1982-review/|first=Lee|last=Jutton|publisher=Film Inquiry|year=2017|accessdate=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Keitai Denj\u016b Telefang]]''\n| Video game\n| 2000\n| 2020\n|The player searches for [[Pok\u00e9mon (video game series)|Pok\u00e9mon]]-esque creatures using mobile phone numbers and battles them.\n|-\n| ''[[Knight Rider 2000]]''\n| TV film\n| 1991\n| 2000\n| In 2000, [[Dan Quayle]] is President of the United States. The United States and the United Kingdom are fighting a war, codenamed Operation Tropical Storm, over [[Bermuda]].<ref>{{cite book | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RxHbPxbBM1AC&pg=PP127 | title=Variety and Daily Variety Television Reviews 1991\u20131992 | volume=17 | last=Prouty | first=Howard H. | isbn=9780824037963 | via=Google Books | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=1994 | chapter=May 21, 1991 }}</ref> Conventional handguns have been banned, with law enforcement carrying non-lethal \"stun\" pistols. Nationwide budget changes have resulted in the adoption of [[Cryonics|cryonic suspension]] over standard incarceration for convicted criminals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wc.arizona.edu/papers/94/78/04_3_m.html|title=Films of the future present \u2013 Tuesday January 16, 2001 \u2013 The Arizona Daily Wildcat|author=|date=|website=Wc.arizona.edu|accessdate=July 31, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Knights of God]]''\n| TV series\n| 1987\n| 2000-2020\n| The Knights of God, a fascist and anti-Christian religious order, came to power in the UK during a brutal civil war in 2000. By 2020, they rule most of Britain. \n|-\n| \"[[L.A. 2017]]\" (from ''[[The Name of the Game (TV series)|The Name of the Game]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1971\n| 2017\n| After a worldwide ecological disaster, the population of Los Angeles moved underground due to the toxic atmosphere in 1989. In 2017, the United States is a [[megacorporation]] and a [[police state]] with its capital in [[Detroit]], and at war with the UK.\n|-\n| ''[[Land of the Giants]]''\n| TV series\n| 1968\n| 1983\n|By 1983, [[sub-orbital flight]]s are established. \n|-\n| ''[[Last and First Men]]''\n| Novel\n| 1930\n|data-sort-value=\"2017\"| Before 2018\n| The Anglo-French War occurs within a century of [[World War I]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Chase]]''\n| Film\n| 1981\n| 2011\n| In 2011, the United States was a [[police state]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Man on Earth (1924 film)|The Last Man on Earth]]''\n| Film\n| 1924\n| 1950\n|A plague of \"masculitis\" leaves just one fertile man left alive in a world of women.\n|-\n| ''[[The Last Man on Earth (1964 film)|The Last Man on Earth]]''\n| Film\n| 1964\n| 1968\n| An adaptation of ''[[I Am Legend (novel)|I Am Legend]]''.\n|-\n| ''[[Last Rights (miniseries)|Last Rights]]''\n| TV miniseries\n| 2005\n| 2009\n| In 2009, [[voter apathy]] is at an all-time high in the [[United Kingdom]], and a new right-wing political party, The Democratic Consensus Party has just been voted into office. Unbeknownst to the public, the DCP has a sinister hidden agenda to do away with democracy and turn the country into a [[police state]].\n|-\n| ''[[The Lathe of Heaven]]''\n| Novel\n| 1971\n| 1998\u20132002\n|Set in a dystopian future wracked by global warming and overpopulation. The main character can retroactively alter reality, creating [[parallel universe (fiction)|alternate realities]], so many of the novel's predictions are undone, including a [[nuclear war]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/books/index.ssf/2009/06/essay_the_lathe_of_heaven_and.html|title='The Lathe of Heaven' and Portland geography: Ursula K. Le Guin's vision|author=|date=June 27, 2009|website=oregonlive.com|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Legend of Bishin]]''\n| Video game\n| 1993\n| 2020\n|[[Mount Fuji]] erupts catastrophically.\n|-\n| \"[[Letters of Transit]]\" (from ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 2012\n| 2015\n| Although most of the episode takes place in 2036, there is mention of a 2015 when the Observers took over the planet and initiated a purge of the populace.\n|-\n| ''[[Lifeforce (film)|Lifeforce]]''\n| Film\n| 1985\n| 1986\n| The film depicts an alien invasion timed to the [[Halley's Comet#1986|1986 return of Halley's Comet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denofgeek.com/us/movies/lifeforce/135942/tobe-hoopers-lifeforce-comet-based-vampire-madness|title=Tobe Hooper's Lifeforce: Comet-based Vampire Madness|author=|date=|website=denofgeek.com|accessdate=December 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Light of Other Days]]''\n| Novel\n| 2000\n| 2010\u20132019\n| Correctly predicted the [[Brexit|United Kingdom deciding to withdraw from the European Union]] in the 2010s and the destruction of a [[Space Shuttle]] in the 2000s.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=ejQ6Oc-VKJQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=the+light+of+other+days+stephen+baxter#v=snippet&q=united%20kingdom&f=false |title = The Light of Other Days|isbn = 9780812576405|last1 = Clarke|first1 = Arthur C.|last2 = Baxter|first2 = Stephen|date = January 15, 2001}}</ref>\n|-\n|\"[[Lisa's Wedding]]\" (from ''[[The Simpsons]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1995\n| 2010\n|The episode depicts [[Big Ben]] as a digital clock that has not yet been properly set (i.e., it still shows 12:00). Emotional robots are common and car engines make the same sound as the flying cars in ''[[The Jetsons]]''.\n|-\n| \"[[A Logic Named Joe]]\" (from ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'')\n| Radio drama\n| 1950\n| 1974\n| An adaptation of the 1946 short story by [[Murray Leinster]]. In 1974, networked personal computers known as logics can be found in almost every home.\n|-\n| \"[[The Long Morrow]]\" (from ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1964\n| 1987\u20131988\n| In 1988, the astronaut Commander Douglas Stansfield is sent on an exploratory mission to a planetary system roughly 141 light-years from Earth.\n|-\n| ''[[Looking Backward]]''\n| Novel\n| 1888\n| 2000\n| In 2000, the United States is a socialist utopia. The novel predicted [[debit card]]s/credit cards and shopping malls.<ref name=\"bustle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/61867-10-times-science-fiction-predicted-the-future-from-credit-cards-to-earbuds|title=10 Times Science Fiction Predicted The Future, From Credit Cards To Earbuds|first=JR|last=Thorpe|date=|work=bustle.com|accessdate=April 15, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"huffpost\">{{cite web|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/18/sci-fi-books-future_n_4117268.html|title=These 7 Books Predicted The Future With Eerie, Almost Unbelievable Accuracy|author=|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=April 15, 2017|publisher=[[Huff Post]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[The Long Watch]]''\n| Short story\n| 1949\n| 1999\n| In 1999, an international organization known as the Space Patrol has custody of all Earth's remaining nuclear weapons. By this time, there is a moonbase.\n|-\n| ''[[Lord of the World]]''\n| Novel\n| 1907\n|data-sort-value=\"2000\"|1917-ca. 2000<ref>{{cite web|title=Introduction to Benson's \"Lord of the World\"|author=Father John McCloskey|url=https://www.catholicity.com/mccloskey/lord-of-the-world.html|accessdate=2018-04-24}}</ref>\n|Since the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] took control of the British Government in 1917, the [[British Empire]] has been a [[single party state]]. The [[British Royal Family]] has been deposed, the [[House of Lords]] has been abolished, [[Oxford University|Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]] have been closed down and all their professors sent into [[Exile|internal exile]] in [[Ireland]]. The [[Anglican Communion]] was [[Disestablishmentarianism|disestablished]] in 1929 and, like all forms of [[Protestantism]], is almost extinct. The world now has only three main religious forces: Catholicism, [[secular humanism]], and \"the Eastern religions.\" The novel predicted widespread use of [[heavier-than-air craft]].\n|-\n| ''[[Lost in Space]]''\n| TV series\n| 1965\u20131968\n| 1997\n| ''Jupiter 2'', the main ship of the series, was launched on October 16, 1997. By this time, Earth is severely [[Human overpopulation|overpopulated]]. The Robinsons were on a mission to colonize [[Alpha Centauri]].\n|-\n| ''[[MAG: Massive Action Game]]''\n| Video game\n| 2010\n| 2020\n| The second war of the S.V.E.R starts off in 2020.\n|-\n| ''[[Make Room! Make Room!]]''\n| Novel\n| 1966\n| 1999\n| The world is overpopulated at 7 billion people, with 35 million people in New York City alone. The inspiration for the film ''[[Soylent Green]]'' (1973).\n|-\n| ''[[Malevil]]''\n| Novel\n| 1974\n| data-sort-value=\"1999\"| The late 20th century\n| Set in a French castle during the outbreak of a nuclear war. Was made into [[Malevil (film)|a film]] in 1981.\n|-\n|''[[The Manchurian Candidate (2004 film)|The Manchurian Candidate]]''\n| Film\n| 2004\n| 2008\n| The film's plot revolves around the then-future [[2008 United States presidential election]].\n|-\n| \"[[Man from 1997]]\" (from ''[[Conflict (TV series)|Conflict]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1956\n| 1997\n| By 1997, time travel is in common use. A librarian named B. O. Boyne from 1997 accidentally leaves an almanac from the future behind when he visits 1956.\n|-\n| ''[[Manhunter: New York]]''\n| Video game\n| 1988\n| 2004\n|The world has been conquered by aliens. \n|-\n| ''[[The Man Who Rocked the Earth]]''\n| Novel\n| 1915\n| 1916\n| In 1916, [[World War I]] had an even more devastating effect than before. Germany conquered Holland, Denmark and Switzerland, Italy annexed [[Dalmatia]] and the [[Trentino]] and a \"Slav republic\" was formed which was composed of [[Hungary]], [[Croatia]], [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Herzegovina]], [[Serbia]], [[Romania]], [[Montenegro]], [[Albania]] and [[Bulgaria]]. The United States remained neutral, as did the newly formed United States of South America which was composed of the Spanish-speaking South American republics. The monarchs of Germany, Italy and the United Kingdom all voluntarily [[Abdication|abdicated]] and those countries became republics.\n|-\n| ''[[The Man Who Sold The Moon]]''\n| Novel\n| 1951\n| 1978\n|By 1978, the Moon has yet to be landed on and a self-described \"[[robber baron (industrialist)|robber baron]]\" bluffs and schmoozes his way towards purchasing it, particularly through ''[[cuius est solum, eius est usque ad coelum et ad inferos]]'' and that the equatorial countries that the Moon passes over must have a claim to its land.\n|-\n| \"[[Mars Is Heaven!]]\"\n| Short story\n| 1948\n| 1960\n| In 1960, the third exploratory spaceship from Earth arrives on Mars. In the ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'' radio adaptation in 1950, the first Earth ship XR-53 lands on Mars on April 20, 1987.\n|-\n| ''[[The Martian Chronicles]]''\n| Short stories\n| 1947\u20131950\n| 1999\u20132026\n| Short stories about humans living on a terraformed Mars.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://science.howstuffworks.com/terraform.htm|title=How Terraforming Works|author=|date=October 3, 2014|website=HowStuffWorks|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref> A 1997 edition of the book advances all the dates by 31 years, thus running from 2030 to 2057.\n|-\n| ''[[Martian Gothic: Unification]]''\n| Video game\n| 2000\n| 2019\n| [[Survival horror]] game set in the first [[Colonisation of Mars|colony on Mars]]. \n|-\n| \"The Martian Death March\" (from ''[[Dimension X (radio program)|Dimension X]]'')\n| Radio drama\n| 1951\n| 1997\n| By 1997, humanity has colonized Mars.\n|-\n| ''[[Mega Man 2]]''\n| Video game\n| 1988\n| data-sort-value=\"2001\"| 200X\n|By the 2000s, artificially intelligent robots are common.<ref name=\"ocweekly\"/><ref name=\"gamesradar\"/><ref name=\"defunct games\"/>\n|-\n| ''[[Memoirs of the Twentieth Century]]''\n| Novel\n| 1733\n| 1997\u20131998\n| Predicts the dominance of [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]] in the 20th century. The novel correctly predicted that the [[Ottoman Empire]] would collapse in the 20th century and that a British monarch named [[George VI]] would reign during that century.\n\n|-\n| ''[[Memory Run]]''\n| Film\n| 1995\n| 2015\n|The world is a [[corporate republic]], and [[body transplant]]s are in beta.<ref>{{cite web|title=Memory Run|url=https://www.scifi-movies.com/en/short/0001514/memory-run-1995/|publisher=scifi-movies.com|accessdate=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Men into Space]]''\n| TV series\n| 1959\u20131960\n|data-sort-value=\"1975\"| {{Circa}} 1975\u20131985\n|The series was not set in a specific era, but clues throughout the scripts indicated that it took place in the mid-1970s to mid-1980s, with the first [