0171005000822/http://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A0DE4DD153EF932A1575AC0A960948260|archive-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badmovies.org/movies/radiodreams/|title=Radioactive Dreams : B-Movie Review|website=Badmovies.org|accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Raid 2020]]''\n| Video game\n| 1989\n| 2020\n| The police force is almost completely corrupt.\n|-\n| ''[[Real Steel]]''\n| Film\n| 2011\n| 2020\n| Human boxers are replaced by robots.\n|-\n| ''[[Rebuild of Evangelion]]''\n| Film series\n| 2007\u20132009 <!-- 2.0 was released in 2009 -->\n| 2015\n| Reboot of ''[[Neon Genesis Evangelion]]''. The first two films take place starting in 2015.<!--  Evangelion 3.0 takes place 14 years after 2.0 -->\n|-\n| ''[[Reign of Fire (film)|Reign of Fire]]''\n|Film\n|2002\n|2008, 2020\n| The introductory part of the film, in which dragons are found under London, is set in 2008, with the remainder set in 2020, in a post-apocalyptic Earth overrun with dragons.\n|-\n| \"[[Resurrection (The Outer Limits)|Resurrection]]\" (from ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]]'')\n| TV series episode\n| 1996\n| 1997\u20132009\n| On July 24, 1997, humanity destroyed itself (as well as all other mammals) in a [[Biological warfare|biological war]] in what became known as the Day of Silence or the Biocaust. Only a few hundred [[Android (robot)|androids]] were left to populate the Earth. In 2009, two androids created a human, Cain, from unaffected DNA samples to lead the Second Coming of humankind.\n|-\n| ''[[Revengers Tragedy]]''\n| Film\n| 2002\n| 2011\n|Sci-fi adaptation of ''[[The Revenger's Tragedy]]'' set in a [[post-apocalyptic]] Great Britain that has been devastated by a natural disaster. \n|-\n|''[[Revolution X]]''\n|Video game\n|1994\n|1996\n| Takes place in a dystopian future where music, television and video games are banned, and the rock band [[Aerosmith]] is kidnapped.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ultimate-guitar.com/article